"{\"uid\": \"nj.com-olympics-2024-07-hezly-rivera-wont-compete-in-the-paris-olympics-gymnastics-final-will-she-still-get-a-medal.html\", \"text\": \"PARIS -Bad news for Hezly Rivera's new legion of fans: The 16-year-old gymnast from Oradell is not expected to compete in Tuesday's team final, according to atweet from USA Gymnasticsout in advance of the much-anticipated competition.  It is still possible that Rivera could step in for another competitor on the balance beam or the uneven bars, her two strengths. That could depend on the health of U.S. star Simone Biles, who was nursing a calf injury during Sunday's qualification round.  For now, though, this is the lineup:  Vault:Jordan Chiles, Jade Carey, Biles  Uneven bars:Chiles, Biles, Suni Lee  Balance beam:Chiles, Lee, Biles  Floor exercise:Lee, Chiles, Biles  No matter what happens, though, Rivera will get a medal if the heavily favored American team finishes in the top three on Tuesday at Bercy Arena. Rivera competed in the qualifying portion of the team competition in both the bars and the beam.  Rivera is the youngest of the nearly 600 athletes in Paris as part of Team USA. She was a surprise inclusion on the U.S. team after a series of injuries knocked out more seasoned competitors, but is expected to be a big part of the Americans' future in international competition.  The team competition begins at 12:15 p.m. ET.  MORE N.J. OLYMPICS:  I have found the Jerseyiest place at the Paris Olympics  Rutgers 'power couple' finds joy in shared Olympic dream  Two N.J. swimmers turned a Somerset County pool into an Olympic hotbed  How a real-life Jersey Jedi plans to fence his way to a gold medal  The unsinkable Molly Reckford is an inspiration for all 'middling' athletes  Meet Amy Wang, New Jersey's pingpong prodigy  Thank you for relying on us to provide the journalism you can trust. Please consider supporting us with a subscription.  Steve Politi may be reached atspoliti@njadvancemedia.com.  Steve Politi is the sports columnist for NJ Advance Media. He has won top honors from the Associated Press Sports Editors in columns (2018 and 2023), long feature (2021) and investigations (with Matt Stanmyre...more  Use of and/or registration on any portion of this site constitutes acceptance of ourUser Agreement, (updated 8/1/2024) and acknowledgement of ourPrivacy Policy,andYour Privacy Choices and Rights(updated 10/1/2025).  \\u00a92025Advance Local Media LLC. All rights reserved (About Us).The material on this site may not be reproduced, distributed, transmitted, cached or otherwise used, except with the prior written permission of Advance Local.  Community Rulesapply to all content you upload or otherwise submit to this site.  YouTube's privacy policyis availablehereandYouTube's terms of serviceis availablehere.  Ad Choices\"}"